				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Keep in mind that using a status bar together with 4-way scrolling can be tricky, because the status bar limits how much you can scroll vertically. SMB3 for example has a maximum level height of 2 name tables minus the status bar. Crystalis uses IRQs to "skip" over the status bar, preventing it from being displayed in the middle of the game screen. But the simplest solution is to use single screen mirroring, because you dedicate one of the name tables to the gameplay and the other to the status bar, and they'll never overlap. I don't think the MMC3 supports single screen mirroring though.</div>
<br />
<br />Here's another method, used by Gargoyle's Quest II, which allows unlimited vertical scrolling: Horizontal mirroring, keep the status bar in the bottom of the second nametable, mirror writes from the first nametable to the second nametable, avoiding overwriting the status bar. Then, you just split the screen on the bottom to show the status bar.
<br />
<br />When your scrolling gets low enough such that the status bar would start scrolling onto screen, the screen split <em>for</em> the status bar will cover it up. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" />
<br />
<br />Anyway, regarding your code, I honestly can't see any reason for it to not work. Theoretically, you resetting $2006 should cause the PPU to drop everything it's doing and start drawing from that exact location. I've definitely split the screen like that before, and it worked, but I don't have the source code for it anymore.
<br />
<br />The only thing I can suggest is to try the method mentioned in Brad Taylor's doc like thefox said. (where you write $2006, then $2005, then $2005 again, then finally $2006 again) I've done this method to have a status bar at the top of the screen (and 4-way scrolling under it), and it worked like a charm.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />-Drag</div>
