				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sat Feb 12, 2005 9:43 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 5251<br /><b>Location:</b> Rio de Janeiro - Brazil
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Drag wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">SMB3 already writes data to both nametables whenever you scroll horizontally. The only difference with GQ is that you're <em>also</em> writing to the nametables when you scroll vertically. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /> The fact that GQ writes mirrored data and SMB3 writes unique data is irrelevent to the PPU; it takes the same amount of writes, regardless.</div>
<br />SMB3 doesn't HAVE to write two screens worth of tiles when it scrolls horizontally though, this was just a design choice so that it wouldn't have to write any tiles when scrolling vertically. In theory, SMB3 would be making better use of the PPU bandwidth if it updated only 1 screen worth of tiles, either horizontally or vertically when necessary, so that in frames that only needed one kind of update, the rest of the time could be used for something else.
<br />
<br />That said, having to write to both name tables, both horizontally and vertically in case diagonal scroll happens, is a big waste of PPU bandwidth in my opinion. Lots of games could live with that, sure, but when you have more PPU updates not related to the scrolling, such as middle-of-the-screen name table changes or pattern table updates (these really demand a lot of time), the time spent copying repeated data will be missed.</div>

